\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-360\ri-998\sa820\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs22\b1\i0\cf1	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs22\b1\i0\cf1 Brief History Of Growing Importance:}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1  Has changed across time. While "space, which is much easier to conceive than time, has been largely neglected" now we have Fredric Jameson (1991) - the 'spatial turn' - Ryan calls it 'spatiotemporal' - paralleled by interest in what Margaret wilson talking about \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93situated cognition\u8221\'94 (2002) - . \u8220\'93The environment is part of the cognitive system\u8221\'94, grounded cognition (Barsalou) and embodied cognition - \u8220\'93The importance of space has been reasserted in recent years.\u8221\'94 - Setting used to be seen as an \u8220\'93empty container\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93Spatial literary studies\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93Bridging the divide between the word and the world\u8221\'94 - Ryan's edited book on 'narrating space'. " space is not simply setting; it produces symbolic and emotional meaning, organizes plots, directs patterns of reader engagement, and orients readers effectively to both the spaces within stories and those weencounter and inhabit." - "we cannot think effectivelyabout narrativewithout thinking about space.\u8221\'94 - "a site of negotiation of the lived, experiential qualities conveyed by a story." - From 'container conception' (Caraciolo) - the connection between place and meaning\u8209\'2Dmaking has been foundational for human geography since the 1970s, and in particular since Yu\u8209\'2DFu Tuan\u8217\'92s Space and Place." - "through embodied, emotional, and intersubjective engagements guided by socio\u8209\'2D cultural practices" - Withers - spatial turn - \u8220\'93place as social practice\u8221\'94 - "The spatial is connected to and debated in literally every possible arena of human thinking." - Simon Schama talks about how identity, myth, memory and emotions are intimately connected to place. Embodied with ideals. Owain Jones - "life is inherently spatial, and inherently emotional" - we use memory, and meotion, and space to orient ourselves in our lives. Make sure I relate it to 1.4. Alexander References Foucault's proclamation that the spatial was more important than the temporal in the modern age (1967). Make it clear that all these fields are coming into the same Venn from different directions.  Actor network theory - Landscape = "where we do everything - Phenom of landscape - LS = "a long-lived dynamic entity deserving explanation" - "The idea of landscape as a set of relational places linked by pathways, movements and narratives". \u8220\'93landscape is fundamental to human existence because it provides both a medium for, and an outcome of, individual and social practices\u8221\'94 - landscapes, in abstract, are formed of places and the paths between them.geocriticism, westphal - space has become really important - 19th century was dominated by "the discourse of time... and teleological development" - Talks about the 'spatial turn' - "geocriticism attempts to understand the real and fictional spaces that we inhabit..." the postmodern or 'post-postmodern condition" - Post-positivist, away from empirical, rational approach - space is not "the empty container" autocosmic is part of this, as well! Westphal, in his introduction, gives an overview of how space has always been symbolic.- "the fruits of a symbolic system, of a speculative movement". Champion - \u8220\'93"To view a place as a container of x y and z dimensions is to deny it a cultural content. A place is more like a nexus, or a web. "  }
