\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Drawing on what talked about in chapter 1 - a being in an environment, interested in environment and all its components, the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93evolution of human cognition\u8221\'94 (Morris-Kay), and as beings with 'bodies located in space'(Wilson 2002) - \u8220\'93The development of an individual from embryo to adult involves a continual interaction between the animal\u8217\'92s genetic makeup and its environment\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93True to phenomenologist doctrine, these authors believe that the most fundamental human experience consists of apprehending oneself as a body located in space.\u8221\'94 Dennett\u8217\'92s physical stance. Focussed on what is important to us. Looking for significance that relates to those desires. Ryan defines four features of worlds: \u8220\'93connected set of objects and individuals; habitable environment; reasonably intelligible totality for external observers; field of activity for its members\u8221\'94 (Ryan, 2001, p. 91).}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Crucially a }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf1 systemic}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1  interest, systemic narratives about place, \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93relational epistemologies\u8221\'94 (Bird-David) - understanding it as a system, \u8220\'93their study of how things-in-situations relate to the actor-perceiver and, from the actor-perceiver\u8217\'92s point of view, to each other\u8221\'94, which is part of practical knowledge (refer back to Sugiyama etc. in Chapter 1). Responding to a complex system all around us that is necessary to our survival. Dennett\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91design stance\u8217\'92. "cybernetic/systemic ecology". Narratives, lines of understanding, causations, systemic narratives, mental models. Yi Fu Tuan takes reader-response approach to our experience of place. Drawing on Paul Shepherd - "only a person who could \u8220\'93establish lines of connectedness or relationship\u8221\'94 (think and act according to totemic and animistic concepts) with the natural world could survive." Sagan - \u8220\'93the myths and folklore of many premodern cultures has explanatory or at least mnemonic value. In stories that everyone can appreciate or even witness, they encode the environment.\u8221\'94 Landscape was not dead - it DID react back. Difference between \u8220\'93operational environment\u8221\'94 (real world) and \u8220\'93cognised encironment\u8221\'94 (how human beings experience that world) (Rapaport). Using our \u8216\'91umwelts\u8217\'92, interpreting our \u8216\'91semiotic niche\u8217\'92. This supported in modern day by biosemiotics (Kull et al, Sebeok) - how signs and meaning are passed around ecologies, the creation and manipulation of meaningful signs how things appear to each other, on lots of different levels. Meaning attribution \u8216\'91stabilises\u8217\'92 processes and allow us to build on them and work with them. \u8220\'93The interpretive capacity is an emergent property of a reciprocal end-means relationship of a self-propagating dynamical system.\u8221\'94 Also actor-network theory. Other cybernetic theories of biology. Meaning exterior (what signs are projected) and meaning interior (how signs are interpreted). \u8220\'93The unknown is so inflammatory to the imagination because it is an imaginative malleable space: a projection-screen on to which a culture or an individual can throw their fears and aspirations.\u8221\'94 Ambiguity in nature. Rappaport - "on populations in the ecological sense, that is, as one of the components of a system of trophic exchanges taking place within a bounded area." (Biersack,1999,5) The cognized model according to Rappaport is the "model of the environment conceived by the people who act in it," (Wolf,1999, 19). \u8220\'93a predictive strategy of interpretation \u8220\'93 - Koenig's imaginative systems - parsing systems and then having a strategy - the 'operational environment'\tab  Rappaport in which we exist and act as organisms becomes part of the 'cognised environment'. Not just for humans. 'in trophic exhanges' Biersack of varying significances to that particular animal's 'significant surround'. a constant 'interpretative challenge' by all elements of that environment to 'establish lines of connectedness' (Paul Shepherd) \u8216\'91Predictive strategy\u8217\'92 (Koenig). actor-network theory - social and natural worlds are relationship systems between actors in networks. all about process and dynamic between factors. Bruno Latour 2005 a reference - A post-structuralist approach - the 'actor-network' - related to Guattari's rhizomes - Emergence in a system from components - punctualisation - all actors are made up of smaller actors. Become 'tokens' or 'quasi-objects'. "Stories tell about the actions of intelligent agents. These agents are situated within a world, and so are the objects they act upon. One may infer from this description that telling a story necessitates, in the words of David Herman \u8220\'93modeling, and enabling others to model, an emergent constellation of spatially related entities.\u8221\'94" - Remember distinctions between geographic space and symbolic space - still are inherently relational in nature. We enjoyed 'pattern-making' - The cognitive activity underlying pattern-making is complex, involving planning and intention, but the original idea of pattern may be a function of the brain - "Roger M. Downs and David Stea argue that \u8220\'93cognitive mapping is a process composed of a series of psychological transformations by which an individual acquires stores, recalls, and decodes information about the relative locations and attributes of the phenomena in his everyday spatial environment\u8221\'94 (qtd. in Kitchin and Freundschuh 2000, 1)". they are "labs" for turning hypothetical experience into real experience. "complex new model" of categorisation in early humans of their environment. (Talking about Levi-Strauss' work) - important signs were made into symbols. a "dynamic map... coming into being" storytelling both helps remember this map and activates its symbols, folding them into everyday behaviours.}
