\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 ELITE MAGIC AND PRACTICE - science and magic wrapped up together, "[of an] identity with" and preceded by the natural philosophy of the 17th century and the "natural magic" (Clark, 1999) of the 15th and 16th centuries, reflected early challenges of the church's hegemony in the mental life of the country, as well as an official, or "elite" (Wilby, 2005) disdain for superstitious beliefs. Watching the systems of nature - Montaigne\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s Watchmaker. A new way to understand and parse natural systems - away from religion. Natural theology - \u8220\'93to scrutinise nature, to discern its patterns and its idiosyncrasies, was thus a form of worship\u8221\'94. It had an \u8220\'93identity with science\u8221\'94 - studying the natural world as a system of secrets, it was \u8220\'93exoteric.\u8221\'94 Keckermann - \u8220\'93extraordinary virtues\u8230\'85 in natural things\u8221\'94 - joining and combining. \u8220\'93Natural magic as a science of the occult\u8230\'85 occult causation\u8221\'94 - battled against superstition, but both attempts to know the unknown. Davies - \u8220\'93natural magic was considered by many intellectuals to be a branch of the sciences, as it dealt with the occult powers within nature.\u8221\'94 References neo-platonism (char as enviro). Low magic and high magic distinction. Needed to deal with a natural world that needed comprehension - a \u8220\'93causal scheme\u8221\'94 (231). \u8216\'91Mechanical\u8217\'92 philosophy came later - Cartesian mechanomorphism - did not remove \u8220\'93occult qualuities\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93Natural magic\u8221\'94 as \u8220\'93applied science\u8221\'94 - unexplained but natural phenomena that are seen as magic. Owen Davies - natural magic was well-tolerated - \u8220\'93hidden or occult natural forces existed in God\u8217\'92s universe that could be tapped by humans\u8221\'94. P 163- quaots perrault calling rhe Devil a great naturalist. Nature was his realm of influence. Superstition could be demonic - it tried to transcend nature\u8217\'92s dvine laws, originated in devils, go beyond \u8220\'93ascertainable limits\u8221\'94 of nature. \u8220\'93The devil was invoked whenever methods of acquring knolwedge assumed causal connections in nature that did not exist\u8221\'94. God gave everything its place in nature - \u8220\'93natural divination\u8221\'94 (scientific observation) vs. \u8220\'93Diabolocial divination\u8221\'94 (Caspar Peucer). Demonology opposed to \u8220\'93natural magic\u8221\'94 - the natural world causing \u8220\'93mira\u8221\'94 - unexplained things. A neoplatonist position. Was natural wisdom - \u8220\'93knowledge of hidden things\u8221\'94. The resonance of the Devil. Fictional characters tied to natural systems, lying behind natural systems. Darwin influenced by Lyell\u8217\'92s work - \u8220\'93the world is the result of natural laws and forces that are active and observable in the present-day world\u8221\'94 - Science as \u8220\'93our own peculiar form of magic\u8221\'94 (arcana mundi) - Ethologists speak about design - mean how a system self-regulates mechanisms. Spinoza's ideas on god i nnature - "an atheist or a pantheist". \u8220\'93Locate the secret forces in nature\u8221\'94 Science and magic interrelate. Lily Alexander - she gives an overview of romanticism - drawing back in early religious practices and beliefs to art. Cities as environs as well. The sublime is a border between imagination and reason - an autocosmic overwhelming. Largeness, fear, misunderstanding. Use the sublime as the link to fiction. The sublime is different from the beautiful in landscape - (kant) - nonsensical, non-understandable. Can a videogame environment be sublime, as we CAN understand it and find its borders? Sublime - we feel terror and awe because the totality of something, and its place in the logos, extends beyond the bounds of our viewpoint, of our percepton,. (drawing on Kant). For Romantics, language could not grasp it. Going beyond, the unknowability of the system. Taylor outlines how this transcendent worldview changed through the exercise of discipline and reform, which gradually tamed uncontrolled and supernatural forces. Coalescing in the Reformation, and affected through a growing middle class, this process of discipline corralled disruptive beliefs and isolated the now buffered self from nature, with the aim of securing a well-ordered and industrious society. }
