\par\plain {\f1\fs22\b1\i0\cf1 Environments/Landscapes In Fiction: }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The importance of space. Mark J. Wolf, refer back to cosmos/worldliness from chapter 1. Interesting link to the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91designedness\u8217\'92 of space. "Lotman views the world of a story as structured by a system of relations between symbolic domains delimited by spatial boundaries." For Wolf, we expand the worlds too (in Tolkien review) through reader participation. "Wolf\u8217\'92s key argument here is since Plato\u8217\'92s Republic, imaginary worlds have existed for their own sake, not merely as narrative settings." - perdurant, just like characters. Imaginary worlds as "transmedia entities, the receptacles of interrelated narratives, or objects of study and interest in themselves". Calls it "subcreation studies" - tolkien's term. He explores them through linguistic, social, cultural, anthropological, geographic, political - "world consistency" - rodrigo lesa and joao araujo and "world completeness" (benjamin j. robertson). Use them for lots of reasons - as uchronias, as political experiments (edward castronova), as satire (carstocea), as places to escape (lars konzack), as participatory (freeman), as dystopias. Fictional worlds are important to narrative art, in and of themselves. Possible Worlds Theory (Ryan, from website) - "accessibility relation" to the real world. Tied to how we percieve environment - deeply tied not just to place, but systemic space/place.Only really need to touch on it. Possible worlds as "ontologically complete entities" - "a matter of missing information, not of ontological deficiency" (some dissent to this idea, she shows). Alison (GS) - \u8220\'93Wuthering Heights as environment as part of story\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93According to Lotman, narrative is born when a character crosses the boundary between these symbolically charged spaces: \u8220\'93A plot can always be reduced to a basic episode\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 the crossing of the basic topological border in the plot\u8217\'92s spatial structure\u8221\'94 ([1970] 1977: 238).\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93all narratives imply a world with spatial extension, even when spatial information is withheld\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93An important aspect of the cognitive mapping of narrative texts is the attribution of symbolic meaning to the various regions and landmarks of the narrative world.\u8221\'94 Jenkins' idea of a story as a 'body of information' rather than 'temporal structure' - Often just seen as settings for human stories. Lawrence Durrell - \u8220\'93You write\u8230\'85 as if the landscape were more important than the characters\u8217\'92 - seeing characters \u8216\'91almost as functions of landscape\u8217\'92 - narratologists have long privileged time over space, narrative space remains a relatively unexplored territory. Dictionary of Imaginary places - place as character - worthy of being considered on its own - Jones on stage design - \u8220\'93To bring into being a powerful non-being\u8221\'94 - Hedda Gabler\u8217\'92s room is almost a \u8220\'93presence, a mood\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93it says nothing, but gives everything\u8221\'94 (not a character for him, though). Celia Pearce - - LOTR stories were \u8220\'93developed as a means to explore the worlds\u8221\'94. Always framed in fiction. Always designed. \u8221\'94Landscapes are culture before they are nature; constructs of the imagination projected on to the wood and water and rock___But it should also be acknowledged that once a certain idea of landscape, a myth or vision, establishes itself in an actual place, it has a peculiar way of muddling categories, of making metaphors more real than their referents, of becoming, in fact, part of the scene\u8221\'94. Laure-Ryan in Why WOrlds Now talks about the history of possible worlds theory in science, art, religion. 'World' not meaning planet, but "everything that exists". Possible Worlds started as a philosophical exercise - a way to explain how imagined worlds could function and be spoken about. With speech act theory. Worlds can be non-actual, just like people. "the exact nature of actuality is open to debate". \u8220\'93But Lewis' work was important because it meant truth and falsity could be talked about when talking about possible worlds - we could discuss them _as_ worlds. Breaking down of older ideas that kept distance from fictional works as important - Lewis tried to collapse that idea of real and irreal, and distance. Not just "the suspension of the rules governing speech acts". Worlds are both immersive and interactive, in Ryan's conception. Can "reach out them". "people start engaging with these worlds for their own sake" - move beyond utilitarian concerns and art and storytelling come into being. "our present fascination with imaginary worlds has deep roots in human evolution". "envisages interactions between consciousness and landscape". Margaret Drabble, A Writer's Britain - how landscape has featured in literature. As we have looked at, how " how textual structures activate embodied cognition." Talks about \u8220\'93literary cartography\u8221\'94 - writers create worlds within and without the text. Ackroyd's narratives - "individuals\u8217\'92 freedoms diminished and handed over to the voracious city. " (cities as well). What Ryan calls 'narrative cartography' - the use of mapped space within literature and storytelling, both conceptually (metatextually) and actually (textually)- plot mappings, geographical mappings, meaning mappings, textual mappings. \u8220\'93We tend to project forms of spatiality onto [the text]\u8221\'94.\u8220\'93We must,\u8221\'94 Ackroyd argues, \u8220\'93regard it [London] as a human shape with its own laws of life and growth.\u8221\'94 The author must submit to the city\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93monstrous form.\u8221\'94 A tension between landscape and character in books, for Weston. Robert Tally Jr. Points out the importance of landscape, \u8216\'91setting\u8217\'92, to narrative. The importance of space has been reasserted in recent years. Setting used to be seen as an \u8220\'93empty container\u8221\'94. The \u8220\'93spatial turn\u8221\'94 - across cultures. \u8220\'93Spatial literary studies\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Bridging the divide between the word and the world\u8221\'94 The \u8220\'93possible worlds\u8221\'94 of literary and fictive philosophy. Withers - spatial turn - \u8220\'93place as social practice\u8221\'94. "narrative\u8217\'92s tendency to foreground human protagonists, psychological causality, and human-scale temporality and spatiality" as Schneider (2001) observes, space in narrative usually serves as a background for characters and their actions, and not as a focus of interest. Environment in art - what Robert Tally calls literary cartography. This is a brief history of the growing importance of personal, face-to-faces engagement with SYSTEMIC environment. And goes on to talk about non-fiction, engagement with the rest of the world. "geographical and rhetorical functions of space". "if the significance of space is a result of its geographic context and the evolving narrative process, then it functions as both a \u8220\'93container and network\u8221\'94 of information (16)". Chronotope Bahktin. The authors develop five layers of space: the domain or spatial frames; how and why characters move and are contained by geography; setting; story space; storyworld, the story spacecompleted by the audience\u8217\'92s imagination; and universal places where social, political, emotional, or cultural boundaries are crossed within a narrative. "s a matter of general configuration rather than of specific geography. Good stories make space legible and meaningful by dividing their world into emotionally and symbolically charged subspaces where different experiences are possible and different kinds of events happen." - place in narrative. Caraciolo providing a phenomenological account of 'narrative space' in modern times. Space is as important as time in our 'sense-making' of narrative. Tied to grounded and embodied cognition. Spatial frames, setting, story space, storyworld -> moving out in specificity. Caraciolo is distinguished - spae is not just meaningful and reosnant socially and culturally, but personally and phenomenonologically as well. Being present in storyworld geographically, understanding themes through space, being emotionally involved. 'Embodied reactions'. "De Certeau even argued that every story is a travel story, as it has to include spatial practices that localize events (Certeau 1984)." "in recent years a new approach to exploring texts has been developed in not only literary but also media studies which suggests looking behind the authorial narrative to the actual world the \u8220\'93author\u8221\'94 creates for the narrative and characters of their stories to live and exist in. "That the worlds invented by \u8220\'93authors\u8221\'94 for their narrative are in themselves \u8220\'93dynamic entities\u8221\'94 (3) and that these worlds are transformative, transmedial and transauthorial in nature and therefore compelling objects of inquiry which invite speculation and exploration through imaginative means." , Jenkins' idea of a story as a 'body of information' rather than 'temporal structure'. Lawrence Buell's "environmental imagination", more often found in non-fiction. "We mean a totality made up of concrete things having material substance, shape, texture and color. Together these things determine an \u8216\'91environmental character,\u8217\'92 which is the essence of place. In general, a place is given as such a character or \u8216\'91atmosphere.\u8217\'92 A place is therefore a qualitative, \u8216\'91total\u8217\'92 phenomenon, which we cannot reduce to any of its properties, such as spatial relationships, without losing its concrete nature out of sight\u8221\'94 (1980, 6 and 8)." - it's character. "From the point of view of the \u8216\'91actual actual world\u8217\'92 the worlds of fiction are discourse-created non-actual possible worlds, populated by incompletely specified individuals; but to the reader immersed in the text the TAW is imaginatively real, and the characters are ontologically complete human beings." Now we are into \u8220\'93environmental literary criticism\u8221\'94. Erin James - Econarratology, talking about systemic, environmental concerns. Both concerned with the environment AS IT IS and platonic environments as systems. Has carried over into secularity. - \u8220\'93unchanging individuality\u8221\'94 - its \u8216\'91perdurance\u8217\'92, perhaps.  " how textual structures activate embodied cognition." - \u8220\'93Some stories present space as closed and confining (prison narratives; Anne Frank\u8217\'92s diary), others as open and liberating (narratives of exploration; many travel narratives), and still others as open and alienating (stories of wandering aimlessly in a hostile environment). Confined space occasionally turns into a field of endless discoveries, as does Robinson Crusoe\u8217\'92s island. Through its immensity, space may be perceived as separating (narratives of exile; Odyssey), or its existence may be denied by technology (telecommunications; travel through teletransportation). Narrative may also focus on place, a concept commonly opposed to space by geographers, by immersing the reader in a particular landscape or cityscape. And finally, narratives may highlight the importance of our sense of embodiment for the experience of space by featuring a protagonist whose body grows or shrinks out of human proportions. Novels like Gulliver\u8217\'92s Travels or Alice in Wonderland de-automatize our relation to space by showing how movement, navigation, the handling of objects and interpersonal relations are affected by a change of scale. Characters are relating to space all the time, but  new nature writing mirrors the concerns of academic ecocriticism, which has similarly explored how scientific and cultural understandings of nature have created hierarchical distinctions between the human and non-human through metaphors of empirical mastery or romantic rapture, but which also acknowledges that such myths are, in Jonathan Bate\u8217\'92s words, \u8216\'91necessary imaginings, exemplary stories which help our species to make sense of its place in the world\u8217\'92. The "emotional-spatial" as a key constituent of ourselves, arising from how our emotional selves interpret the spaces around us.\u8221\'94 "During the postwar period, writers grappled with the difficulties that are presented by the very human focus of the novel form. In the same period, creative nonfiction prose concerned with landscape and environment has increasingly deployed a set of literary techniques associated primarily with fiction." Seamus Heaney - landscape as a \u8220\'93cryptic fabric of signs instinct with spiritual significance.\u8221\'94 They are also narratively incomplete. }
