\par\plain {\f1\fs22\b1\i0\cf1 Anthropomorphism/Animism/Animals As Elements Of Environment As Well (In Fiction), i.e. characterising environments: }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Popular cultural forms have a strong anthropomorphic bias\u8221\'94 - "the scope to representations of animals and shows that trans-species empathy relies on the same cognitive processes as human empathy." Focus on 'reciprocity' between human and non-human agencies. Non-human and non-animals can have agencies in these models. Nominalization - turning verbs into nouns - processes into agents. the 'nonhuman turn'. rld". Creating animal autobiographies - a new phenomenon . "strategies for projecting nonhuman experiences in storyworlds" - ranging from 'speaking for' animals (human-centred) to trying to represent their experiences directly. Animals as representatives of their environment. DeMello - become "much more than simply allegorical devices". Is it fiction or real? Can it ever be real? He asks this question. Works of both 'popular and critical posthumanism". "anthropocentric ontologies deny proper selfhood to nonhuman beings". " this other way of configuring creatural life allocates to a whole range of animals possibilities for selfhood that more restrictive ontologies limit to humans\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 or even to only a subset of the larger human population." " these narratives may highlight and even challenge our conception of the human" - narratives can be ABOUT place rather than about humans in place. Going back to the intentional stance, updated to suit what we now know about the world. Both think of in human terms and 'defamiliarise" - a 'double dialectic". Drawing on Blakey Vermeule - the importance of anthropomorphisation and animism. " the conceptual integration of human and non-human traits" empathy and defamiliarisation with landscapes - drawing attention to their otherness, our part in them, our treatment of them. "This rudimentary, proto- typical structure involves the assumption that the entity has mental states and a body (Eder, Jannidis, and Schneider 13)." Janndis' basic character - we can start assuming fairly easily that something non-human can be a character. "stories narrated by non-human animals can destabilize anthropocentric ideologies" - both empathise and other animals. We are p[art of a continuum with them. Can be both familiar and strange, depending on context. " a double dialectic of empathy and defamiliarization (on the one hand), human and non-human experientiality (on the other)". "Object narrators collapse the cognitively basic distinction between animate and inanimate entities". " Combined with narrative empathy, defamiliarization can generate narrative interest by producing startling insights: as our case studies have shown, it can expand the audience\u8217\'92s understanding of the physical world (in the Carey text, the object narrators call attention to invisible natural forces and phenomena)". "challenge anthropocentric worldviews by gesturing towards a dimension of animal experience that is largely unknown to human readers". David Herman - co-authored acts of narrating in behalf of equally hybrid (or \u8220\'93humanimal\u8221\'94) principals. "solidarity-building projections of other creatures\u8217\'92 ways of being-in-the-wo. "Instead, Goatly\u8217\'92s suggestion is that, in order to dispel this myth, \u8220\'93our image of the world has to become one in which processes predominate and human actors disappear\u8221\'94 (1996: 554)". An environmentally oriented text might be more usefully conceived of as one that moves toward establishing a dialogue between the human narrative, on the one hand, and concern for landscape and environment, on the other, perhaps even only tentatively. Animism today is "the offspring of the early human;s belief systems". Narratology Beyond The Human - \u8220\'93post-darwinian narratives\u8221\'94 - having an animal/human narrative is not simple -