ut not too far.\u8220\'93enchanted, and thereby manifesting a reality beyond exhaustive rational human conceptualization.\u8221\'94 "the scope to representations of animals and shows that trans-species empathy relies on the same cognitive processes as human empathy." - \u8220\'93 the ideal of neighbourly cohabitation that is at the heart of the new nature writing\u8221\'94. H is For Hawk - an animal as a landscape, as an extension of landscape and something to get to know. Uses very algorithmic language, talking about its different features, something she gets to know, uses as a reflection of her own autocosmic relationship with father, a reflexction of her grief. \u8220\'93Domestic animals are beloved, familiar and invisible, while the fascination and remoteness of wild animals is provoked\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Training a hawk was like psychoanalysis.\u8221\'94 Richard Mabey on W.H. Hudson = \u8220\'93saw all birds as extensions of the landscapes in which they moved\u8221\'94 - chruches without jackdaws are not chruches. \u8220\'93Stimulus: opera. Response: kill\u8221\'94 - like a machine. I am reminded of Henry Moore stating that sheep remind him of living stones.\u8220\'93the workings\u8230\'85 of posture and feathers\u8230\'85 an exquisitely controlled barometer of mood\u8221\'94 Animot - derrida on animals as equals - Who are we following when we follow an animal? We are following ourselves.\u8220\'93An existence that refuses to be conceptualized\u8221\'94 - animal as attempted to understand systemically, on an intimate level, rather than merely a player in a story.Animal conception as inextricable from human perspective.\u8220\'93Immense symbolic responsibility\u8221\'94 of animals. Like Baker\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91Peregrine\u8217\'92 - \u8220\'93remarkable metamorphosis of man into predatory bird\u8221\'94. Away from Hobbesian \u8216\'91artificial animal\u8217\'92 and Cartesian machine-animal, to a still systemic but more mysterious animal. H is for Hawk - \u8220\'93so much of what she means is made of people\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93The complexity (and co-constitutive effects) of human-animal interactions and relationships\u8221\'94. Post-human narratology - beyond \u8220\'93normal narratological science\u8221\'94. Helen Macdonald - \u8220\'93my watching\u8230\'85 the first few days with a wild new hawk are a delicate, reflexive dance of manners\u8221\'94. Bestiality, and its principle of uncertainty, must be killed in animals. Personality in animals - consistent invdividual traits that differ from other animals of the same species. Or are they \u8220\'93mindless automatons\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93prevailing opinion has swung between the two extremes\u8221\'94. Neither Descartes, Kant, Heidegger, Levinas, nor Lacan, he claims, has given such sustained attention to the question of the animal. For Derrida, animals are not different.Baudrillard as well. She feels like a protecting spirit\u8230\'85 my little household god\u8221\'94 - h is for hawk. Gibson - "re-sacralizing animals" Limitrophy - the gaps and inconsistencies in the assumed binary divide between humans and animals. A mix of domestic geography and \u8216\'91wildness\u8217\'92. \u8220\'93Worshipping an iceberg\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93a persuasive reconfiguration of the local\u8221\'94. Beyond \u8220\'93Menzal - animals as \u8220\'93goal-seeking agents that acquire, store, retrieve and internally process information.\u8221\'94 Also an unnatural arrangement (according to heideger) - \u8220\'93The original monstrosity of the beast\u8221\'94 (baudrillard). Allomorphism - \u8220\'93the wonderous strangeness of animals, which often involves an overtly-sacred language.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93That place where goshawks go when they\u8217\'92ve eaten. It is very far away.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Split-second ink-starred decisions in the hawk\u8217\'92s tactical computer\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93A being whose world is drawn in plots and vecotrs that pull her towards lives\u8217\'92 ends\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93Healthy delight for animal\u8230\'85 but with the greatest possible consideration for its biological situation\u8221\'94. In particular, our sentimentality toward animals is a sure sign of the disdain in which we hold them.\u8220\'93All sorts of predatory taxonomies are buried in the baby goshawk\u8217\'92s brain\u8221\'94. Animals "are all beasts of burden, in a sense, made to carry some portion of our thoughts". "whether he likes it or not, [man] must play the part thrust upon him in accordance with the ceremonial peculiar to that species." Despot - subordinate relationship. A psychological competition as well as physical when domineering. Whatever it may be, animals have always had, until our era, a divine or sacrificial nobility that all mythologies recount. Even murder by hunting is still a symbolic relation, as opposed to an experimental dissection. Animals don\u8217\'92t always conform to narratives. Helen Macdonald had to impose a human intentionality to wrangle a narrative out of her bird. umwelt close to the idea of embodied cognition " transposing the environment into its subjective meaning, which is accessible only to the encoding subject." - robot umwelt - the hawk is represented as an experience that we cannot subsume into a system or narrative. Both social and parasocial relationships with animals.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93The idea of using talking animals in the stories (Joe Bear et al.) was Roger\u8217\'92s idea. Clearly, we weren\u8217\'92t going to get very sophisticated or elaborate output from this program, but we could illustrate the basic ideas, and the animals gave it a bit of humor.\u8221\'94 Horses in videogames - unerring companions (Roach, Red Dead, Skyrim/Oblivion, Wander in Shadow of the Collosusalways used to name them in the console), silent, tactical, agents in the countryside, probably the closst. You talk to it - a synaesthetic relationship; your button presses both move the horse and cause your character to touch it - people talking about horses being an extension of them (centaurs, chimera character) in games- an extension of you, or of the landscape. Relating to the landscape. Colours complementing, can already jump fences.  " specific entities such as animals and seas are core in people's mental images of nature (e.g., van den Born,Lenders, de Groot, & Huijsman, 2001)" - nicola taylor - "the personality, and thus the personhood of animals, as intersubjectively and reflexively created. " Animals can be persons distinct from their environments, or part of the 'non-human' environment. Drawing sociology into human-animal relations. Beforehand was dismissive, anthopocentric. "the rich traditions of phenomenological and ethnomethodological sociology which see the mind as a social construction rather than a biological given" - " interaction \u8220\'93can be anything that the participants agree to treat as explicit\u8221\'94 (Drew and Wootton ibidem: 35-36. Author emphasis added)." (non-verbal, part 4)}
