\par\plain {\f1\fs22\b1\i0\cf1 EcoCrit, Nature Writing: }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "Nan Shepherd devises ways of moving outside of straightforward human perspective on environment". CogSci in EcoCrit: emotions created to promote political and social change, environmental texts exert a deep and effective impact on their readers. . Turned out Nice Again (2013) - the weather as a "creature of our imagination" \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The choice between monolithic, ecocidal modernism and reverential awe is a false dichotomy\u8221\'94. Swamp Dragon talking about ecofeminism. In Swamp Dragon - " tired of reverence as the only option". NNW - "deploying techniques drawn from novelistic discourse in their treatment of nonfictional material." About \u8220\'93Human relations with the non-human world\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93we require things to have their own lives if they are to enrich ours\u8221\'94 (McF). A use for the ineffable as well as the scientific. Nature writing bridges science and poetry. Aligned with Psychogeography - mapping mind to a space. Psychogeography (Flanagan) - \u8220\'93a discipline\u8230\'85 to study and experience the effects of environment\u8230\'85 on emotions, thinking processes and behavior\u8221\'94 - started by Situationists. The mixing of the occult in Ian Sinclair\u8217\'92s work. Mabey - \u8220\'93all of us who have tried to explore the complex relationships between humans and the natural world\u8221\'94. Mabey points out that it is difficult to homogenize - ranging from literature to science work, \u8220\'93imaginative travel literature\u8221\'94 of Robert Macfarlane - but all united by love of and evocation of nature? Grouped as a \u8220\'93kind of cult\u8221\'94 - the shamanic tone again? \u8220\'93Most of us prefer to think of ourselves just as writers, who simply wish to embrace a rather larger than usual cast of characters, the other beings and landscapes with which we share the planet \endash  and to respect them as subjects not simply objects. But nature as active subject implies relationships, not simply objective descriptions (that's "natural history writing"), and the difficult work of marrying truth to one's emotional and imaginative responses with truth to an organism's own life.\u8221\'94 Confusing whether nature is an enchanted place, whether we know it through facts or metaphysically, or whether it is transcendant. \u8220\'93The overwhelming complexity and depth of a single place\u8221\'94. cog sci in environmental crit - environmental texts exert a deep and effective impact on their readers. Sinclairs, Ackroyds work blends shamanism and moden landscapes - "channel the resonances of place". "its protagonist is the living mountain itself (the range is taken as a single entity in this respect)". " The topographical features of place\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 the \u8220\'93elementals\u8221\'94\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 make up this environment\u8217\'92s character." "the \u8220\'93quiescence,\u8221\'94 the loosening of self, that is needed for an intimate relationship with this place. She is also clear that she does not \u8220\'93ascribe sentience to the mountain.\u8221\'94 Instead, \u8220\'93consciousness interacts with the mountain-forms,\u8221\'94 resulting in \u8220\'93matter impregnated with mind.\u8221\'9436" - constructs, LIKE characters. Points out Macfarlane saying that nature writing had a new resurgance from 70s onwards. Away from pastoral romanticism. \u8220\'93Ecologically informed aestheticised observation\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93Draw attention to the natural world around us\u8221\'94. \u8220\'93close natural history observation as psychotherapy and psychodrama\u8221\'94. There are issues with it (Oakley et al) - apolitical, elitist, over-romantic. Moran 2014 - personal narratives link to the political and generalised in nature writing. This sense of the obdurate otherness of nature, its mute, unredemptive indifference, is a common trope in the new nature writing. Ecocrit linking to ACTION, using a space - ritual relation to narrative. Descriptions of ritual practices and invitations to perform new ones. \u8220\'93different ways of being alive\u8221\'94. Both action and inaction, travel and \u8216\'91stayputtedness\u8217\'92. the complex relation between literary production and environmental activism - taking action within a space. "Smith\u8217\'92s study does important work towards institutionalising New Nature Writing, consistently treating it as a complex, multifarious genre that is intimately connected to socially engaged environmental activism." Granta 102 - the new nature writing. Also Bloomsbury book on same subject. The \u8220\'93literature of place\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93proliferation of landscape writing in Britain and Ireland\u8221\'94 is both stylistically innovative and mindful of ecology and conservation practice - against homogenisation - the \u8220\'93character\u8221\'94 of place. \u8220\'93unashamedly anthropocentric\u8221\'94 - yes, sometimes... Moran - finding meaning not in the rare and exotic but in our common, unremarkable encounters with the natural world, and in combining both scientific, scholarly observation of nature with carefully crafted, discursive writing. Personal reflection with natural history, cultural history, psychogeography, travel and topographical writing, folklore and prose poetry. all speak to anxieties about human disconnection from natural processes which have grown since the first stirrings of the environmental movement in the early 1970s, Interested in local knowledge, focus on the \u8216\'91parochial\u8217\'92 as a positive. Both natural and cultural landscapes. \u8220\'93Finding words to bridge that divide between the otherness of nature\u8221\'94. Ecocriticism - \u8220\'93the study of the relationship between the human and the non-human\u8221\'94. Several different ways to talk about this idea of relational identity and agency, mixing of human and non-human -a secular approach ot older ideas about nature. - "the non-human, the topography, becomes active". \u8220\'93 Now I warm towards the concept of neighbourliness as a template with which to approach and write about our relations with our fellow organisms. It permits concern, shared circumstance, even love from afar, but demands no reciprocity.\u8221\'94  Not just \u8216\'91nature\u8217\'92 writing - basically, those ways that mankind writes about relationships outside of himself - with places, environments, climates, animals. \u8220\'93a recognition of the appropriate, and therefore intelligent, behaviour of matter, and that landscapes have "memories" embedded in their structure that influence their present environs, their future destinies \endash  and the humans that pass through them.\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93 "new" nature writing was not new at all, but embedded in a long tradition\u8221\'94 - a sentence on its heritage?  a dialogic relationship with places, objects and landscapes: a relationship that is infused with social and cultural characteristics" Palmer, 2014. Combining shamanistic sentiment with solid scientific credentials.  Poole and New Statesman argument seeing it as fashionable solipsism, bordering on religiosity, gatekeeping. \u8220\'93Romantic self-obsession\u8221\'94 I disagree, or even celebrate the religiosity. A mixture of secular, phenomenological ideas and spuirituality. From religion to art. \u8220\'93Material, embodied interactions through which the identities of places and human subjects are co-constructed.\u8221\'94 Attention leads to understanding, empathy and thus political action in favour of landscape - like with a person? (Jos Smith) - \u8220\'93mind \endash  just as with Leach's ascription of reflective consciousness to animals and plants, or Dee's self-questioning wildebeest and knowledgeable gas \endash  is understood to be spread out everywhere in nature, rather than a possession only of human beings. It's probably always a strong temptation for nature writers to flirt with such panpsychism. Doesn\u8217\'92t matter if it is actually there - we can use it. What Mabey calls \u8216\'91the firsthand encounters with nature that are the aboriginal, objective raw material for science and art alike\u8217\'92.[63].  "thoroughgoing embrace of novelistic discourse" for nature writing. The Living Mountain - places being "sinister", known for drownings, can find wherw water comes from, but just makes more mysteries. "The fully embodied engagement with a specific landscape, the dissolving of one\u8217\'92s being, and the transgression of the boundary between the self and other". Not studied much even in 2001 (Carter) - both \u8220\'93intimacy and detachment\u8221\'94 -" As each element, inanimate and animate, \u8216\'91natural\u8217\'92 and \u8216\'91cultural\u8217\'92, makes the \u8216\'91living\u8217\'92 mountain"."Rather, she subverts these discourses and provides an alternative to \u8216\'91a masculinized ideal of selfhood founded on separation from nature, rational objectivity and a need to dominate\u8217\'92 (Kroeber, 1994, p. 17). "a text which moves beyond habitual means of charting the world and unsettles habitual ways of perceiving a landscape, a kind of domestic geography [2] that maps borders and then transgresses them." "This would suggest that the narrative arrangement of her work is spatial rather than temporal, and that the individual is not, in fact, central, but exists as a part of a place and as part of a community." "this is a pallid simulacrum of their reality, which, like every reality that matters to human beings, is a reality of the mind\u8217\'92" - she stands against rational detachment from place, in Carter's view. "Shepherd\u8217\'92s geographical poetics opens up these possibilities for conveying modes of experience that exist beyond the constraints of everyday life" - but also part of everyday life. A definite exploration of "coming to know" a place. Like a person. Refers to mountains as gendered. "coming to be with a friend just to sit with them". She cannot hope to exploit them on her own; but she can make forays into them. Places unknown because of weather or incline have a sanctity. Talks about interiority of the mountain Mystery of water, unknowablity, life of its own. where come from, where does it go. Animals (like ptarmigan) knowable parts of vast unknowability. Just one character, in parts. Must see enviro as a whole. Never in totality, can never know a person in totality. Points out the revival of writers such as Shepherd by the NNWs. Going to a place is like getting to know a stranger - we have not grown up with them (Jamie\u8217\'92s critique of Macfarlane), unlike Shepherd, who consistently went to the same places. Hitt - Eco/geocriticism are the literary/artistic emergences of our autocosmic relationship with nature Hitt - He sees eco-critical texts as criticising earlier works as divorced from actual real nature, instead residing in ideals and the imagination. He sees that need for word and thing to be close as simplistic "drastically narrow" or "misguided in its assumptions about literary representation"}
