\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 On Actor-Network Theory And Landscape - The 'actor', rather than the person - a new way to frame it, doesn't even have to be a person. Remember the difference between 'actor' and 'person'. ANT recognises that allobjects and things exhibit consciousness, and through a consciousness, interact heterogeneously in space; the location of the interaction(s), where they are performed homogeneously, is the landscape. " the nonhuman object exhibits consciousness by being connected to the human actor (or consciousness)." - the network created by consciousness. " objects are connected and networked because they are actors waiting to be activated, but they only become things once meaning is instilled in them". Away from dialectic (binary) to interconnectedness (network) - "ANT\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s paramount significance when studying landscape, allowing the researcher, artist \endash  whoever \endash  to draw upon any entity \endash  theory, object, thing, whatever \endash  in their pursuit for understanding, despite scale, space, place and/or time where they reside" - ANT related to performativity - activities create connections. landscape as a "form or a process" - "ANT suggests that the actor is a number of different things \endash  perhaps human, perhaps nonhuman; maybe conscious, maybe unconscious \endash  and always embodies action (cf. Bruunand Langlais 2003; Butler, 1993). It further suggests that the actor can also be a group of things, and that each thing \endash  as an individual or group \endash  is linked, or networked." - " is best defined as the definitive \u8216\'91stage\u8217\'92 where everyone (and thus, everything) remains involved in production and consumption, whether aware of it or not. "}
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 What Is Posthumanism Cary Wolfe -2010 - Again talking about Foucault's 'The Order Of Things' - Posthumanism traced to cybernetics and system thinking - removing us from any "particularly privileged position" -  For him, humanism involves disembodying the human in order to elevate it. For him, posthumanism was before - it is rooted in an evolutionary, timeless idea of the human, not a new one. Going into Lacan, Zizek - what is real/fake, inside/outside - Deleuze and Guattari's pluralism over dualism. Autocosmic is a pluralist approach. Derrida deconstructing the human/animal divide. "neurophysiological organisation" - beings coming together. The "self-referential formal dynamics of meaning... reduce environmental complexity and interface with the world" Coming out of the the MOVEMENT of systems rather than merely the description of them. "the world is an ongoing, differentiated construction and creation of a shared environment, by... entities that have... their own forms of embodiement" The world and its perception is contingent on the interplay between entity and environment. Maturana and Varela say both open and closed - open at a microscopic level, closed at a top level. Where do we 'close' an environment? Where do we encompass it? "rethink our taken-for-granted modes of human experience" - not closed off, but part of the evolutionary, sensory, semiotic realities of other entities in network.But for such ideals, humanity MUST be considered separately because it has grown up with non-natural technologies, most notably (for Derrida) language. "prosthesis" of the human. "changes how we think about normal human experience and how that experience gets refracted or queried in specific modes and media of artistic and cultural practice" - this is also the role of autocosmics, more specifically - it is more than post-human, though draws on it massively. Narrative is, in a posthumanist sense, the methods by which environmental complexity is processed and reduced }
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Posthumanism - Nayar (2014) - An overview on post-humanism - a 'species cosmopolitanism' - 'drawing attention to the constructed nature f the human 'person'' - from non-usual humans through to non-human persons. "taken-for-granted categories of human/non-human" (and person/non-person too) - "a new understanding of 'life' itself" - scientific, social and cultural advances lead us to question the superiority and alterity of humans vs. the rest of the world.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "treat the human itself as an assemblage" (of different influences and co-evolved environments) "CRITICAL posthumanism" not popular (i.e. cyborgs) - "the human as an instantiation of a network of connections... with all forms of life"}
